{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487206"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:00:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"277"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/277"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.33,0.49,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105627"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29768"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42994"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105627"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic for follow-up of an incidentally discovered ovarian cyst. She is asymptomatic and has no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. Her body mass index is 47 kg/m2. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. A recent pelvic ultrasound report describes \u0022a 40 mm left-sided ovarian cyst with a single loculation but no solid components. Right ovary normal. No ascites.\u0022 Her CA-125 level is 25 U/mL (0-35). The cyst has now been present on two different ultrasounds performed by the patients GP 3 months apart without any interval growth or change. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen and pelvis","Laparoscopic bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy","Monitor with 3-monthly serial pelvic ultrasounds","Reassurance and review in 4-6 months with repeat pelvic ultrasound and tumour markers","Total abdominal hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis postmenopausal woman presents with an incidentally discovered simple ovarian cyst. The most appropriate management in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance and review in 4-6 months\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach is based on the low risk of malignancy as determined by the Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) and the patient\u0027s preference to avoid surgery if safe. Asymptomatic, simple, unilateral, unilocular ovarian cysts, less than 5 cm in diameter, have a low risk of malignancy. In the presence of normal serum CA125 levels, these cysts can be managed conservatively, with a repeat evaluation in 4\u20136 months. It is reasonable to discharge these women from follow-up after 1 year if the cyst remains unchanged or reduces in size, with normal CA125, taking into consideration a woman\u2019s wishes and surgical fitness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe RMI is a scoring system used to assess the risk of malignancy in ovarian masses. It is calculated by multiplying three factors: menopausal status (3 for postmenopausal), ultrasound score (1 point each for multilocular cyst, solid areas, bilateral lesions, ascites, and intra-abdominal metastases), and CA-125 level. In this case, RMI = 3 x 1 x 25 = 75. An RMI \u0026lt; 200 indicates a low risk of malignancy and can be managed by a general gynaecologist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitoring with 3-monthly serial pelvic ultrasounds\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily frequent for a cyst \u0026lt;5cm low RMI. There is no evidence to support such frequent screening, and it may cause undue anxiety for the patient. In this case the patients GP has already performed a serial ultrasound at 3 months with no cyst change and referred for review by the gynaecology team. It would be reasonable to wait for 4-6 months before next clinical review by the gynaecologist as per RCOG guidelines. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate surgical option if the patient desired definitive management or if there were concerning features. However, given the low RMI, conservative management is more appropriate at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The ultrasound findings and CA-125 level provide sufficient information for risk stratification. A CT scan would expose the patient to unnecessary radiation without providing significant additional information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal abdominal hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive for a simple cyst with low RMI. This approach carries higher risks of surgical complications and is not justified based on the current clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe recommended approach of reassurance and review in 4-6 months allows for monitoring of the cyst while avoiding unnecessary interventions. If the cyst remains stable or resolves at the 6-month follow-up, annual surveillance or even discharge may be considered. Any significant changes in size, appearance, or CA-125 level would prompt reconsideration of management options, including possible surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Simple ovarian cysts in postmenopausal women with low Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) can be managed conservatively with periodic follow-up.","The Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) is a useful tool for stratifying ovarian masses and guiding management in postmenopausal women."],"references":["RCOG (2016) The Management of ovarian cysts in postmenopausal women.\u00a0https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/green-top-guidelines/gtg_34.pdf.\u00a0Accessed August 28th, 2020.","Jacobs IJ, Menon U, Ryan A, et al. Ovarian cancer screening and mortality in the UK Collaborative Trial of Ovarian Cancer Screening (UKCTOCS): a randomised controlled trial [published correction appears in Lancet. 2016 Mar 5;387(10022):944] [published correction appears in Lancet. 2016 Mar 5;387(10022):944].\u00a0Lancet. 2016;387(10022):945-956. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(15)01224-6","Nunes N, Ambler G, Foo X, et al. Comparison of two protocols for the management of asymptomatic postmenopausal women with adnexal tumours - a randomised controlled trial of RMI/RCOG vs Simple Rules.\u00a0Br J Cancer. 2017;116(5):584-591. doi:10.1038/bjc.2017.17","Yeoh M. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Jan-Feb;44(1-2):48-52. https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"277"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17891"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17891"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1f21046a-ebf3-4f00-bf12-57f938176e77.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1f21046a-ebf3-4f00-bf12-57f938176e77.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1252,"height":352}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T09:30:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T12:45:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105627"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attribu